      <p>It may be useful to calculate probabilities using a Venn diagram.</p>
      <example>
        <title>Venn Diagram Probabilities</title>
        <p>Recall in Example
          <xref ref="example-disneyland-knotts" /> we considered a survey of
          <m>100</m> people in California indicating that
          <m>60</m> people had visited Disneyland,
          <m>15</m> had visited Knott's Berry Farm, and
          <m>6</m> had visited both.  Determine the following probabilities using the Venn diagram.
        </p>
        <sidebyside widths="40% 55%" valign="middle" margins="0%">
          <paragraphs>
            <p>Let set
              <m>D</m> represent those surveyed who have visited Disneyland.</p>
            <p>Let set
              <m>K</m> represent those surveyed who have visited Knott's Berry Farm.</p>
            <p>We completed the Venn diagram at the right.
            </p>
          </paragraphs>
          <figure xml:id="figure-venn-parks-solution">
            <image xml:id="venn-parks-solution">
              <latex-image-code><![CDATA[
                      \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \draw \universe;
                        \node[anchor=south east] at (current bounding box.south east) {$U$};
                        \node[anchor=south west] at (current bounding box.south west) {$\color{brown}31$};
                        \draw[outline] \firstcircle node[shift={(-1.5,1.5)}] {$D$};
                        \draw[outline] \secondcircle node[shift={(1.5,1.5)}] {$K$};
                        \node[shift={(1,0)}] {$\color{red}{6}$};
                        \node[shift={(0,0)}] {$\color{blue}{54}$};
                        \node[shift={(2,0)}] {$\color{green}{9}$};
                      \end{tikzpicture} ]]></latex-image-code>
            </image>
          </figure>
        </sidebyside>
        <p>(a) Determine the probability that a person surveyed went to Disneyland. Label the event space <m>D</m> for Disneyland.
        <md>
          <mrow>n(D)=54+6=60 \amp\amp\amp \text{The number of people surveyed who went to Disneyland.}</mrow>
          <mrow>P(D) = \dfrac{n(D)}{\text{Total #}}=\dfrac{60}{100}= 0.6 \amp\amp\amp \text{Our Solution (a):}</mrow>
          </md>
          The probability that a person surveyed went to Disneyland is <m>\dfrac{60}{100}</m> or <m>60\%.\checkmark</m>
        </p>
        <p>(b) Determine the probability that a person surveyed went to both parks. Label the event space <m>D\cap K</m> for Disneyland AND Knott's.
        <md>
          <mrow>n(D\cap K)=6 \amp\amp\amp \text{The number of people surveyed who went to both parks.}</mrow>
          <mrow>P(D\cap K) = \dfrac{n(D\cap K)}{\text{Total #}}=\dfrac{6}{100}= 0.06 \amp\amp\amp \text{Our Solution (b):}</mrow>
          </md>
          The probability that a person surveyed went to both parks is <m>\dfrac{6}{100}</m> or <m>6\%.\checkmark</m>
        </p>
        <P>(c) Determine the probability that a person surveyed went to either Knott's or Disneyland (or both). Label the event space <m>D\cup K</m> for Disneyland OR Knott's.
        <md>
          <mrow>n(D\cup K)=54+6+9=69 \amp\amp\amp \text{The number of people surveyed who went to either park (or both).}</mrow>
          <mrow>P(D\cup K) =\dfrac{69}{100}= 0.69 \amp\amp\amp \text{Our Solution (c):}</mrow>
          </md>
          The probability that a person surveyed went to either park is <m>\dfrac{69}{100}</m> or <m>69\%.\checkmark</m>.
        </P>
      </example>
